[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2)  [bold]A personal view of public transport policy and[bold] implementation from a regularly and long-used bus seat[bold]2.1[bold]              [bold]Being a regular bus user on both urban and rural routes over 40 years, starting with schooldays travelling from 
[normal]Windyhaugh
[normal] in the upper Coquet valley to 
[normal]Morpeth
[normal], Northumberland, and then working i
[normal]n various places from East London to mid Wales, Worcestershire to Middlesbrough, returning to Northumberland regularly using public transport, I have had plenty of opportunity for comparison.  
[normal]2.2[bold]              [bold]For the last 9 years I have been in Northumberland, using 
[normal]the 
[normal]Thropton
[normal] to 
[normal]Newcastle
[normal] route for at least 5 return journeys per week between 
[normal]Longframlington
[normal] and 
[normal]Morpeth
[normal], mostly for work or to connect to other destinations, so I have been able to observe all of the changes on this route since 1971.
[normal]2.3 [bold]              [bold]I am submitti
[normal]ng this evidence because I have full awareness of how 
[normal]important [bold]the bus service is for we passengers 
[normal]in all aspects of life, and not just to access shops and basic services.  [bold]Anyone not a regular rural bus user has no conception of this, as is reflected by
[normal] policies and implementation for rural bus services .
[normal]2.4[bold]              [bold]Also I think that the best hope for rural public transport is to enable a proper 
[normal]network[bold] to be 
[normal]run profitably[bold], in recent years 
[normal]hindered by deteriorating communication with existing passengers and la[bold]ck of contact with[bold] [bold]potential[bold] passengers[bold], largely because of  the constraints of funding structures.
[normal]2.5[bold]              [bold]Profitable and appropriate running of public transport in rural areas is hindered by looking at the funding of each route in isolation, instead of examining it as part of an effective and usable public transport [bold]network[bold].[bold]2.6[bold]              [bold]Sources:
