[normal]How do government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities?[bold]3.1[bold]              [bold]Though there were surveys in previous decades, in the last nine years, despite making 
[normal]minimu
[normal], five ret
[normal]urn journeys per week between 
[normal]Longframlington
[normal] and 
[normal]Morpeth
[normal],  I have only seen one County Council survey, in spring 2011, and one done by a national organization, though I have heard that another was done this spring driver about a specific proposed change t
[normal]o our timetable.
[normal]3.2[bold]              [bold]Our parish council has asked for people to notify them of their public transport needs via our parish newsletter, as has 
[normal]Rothbury
[normal], 
[normal]Thropton
[normal],  and upper 
[normal]Coquetdale
[normal], but until very recently, 
[normal]Longhorsley
[normal], the other main village on our bus
[normal] route did not have such a publication.
[normal]3.3[bold]              [bold]Our weekly, “Northumberland Gazette” covers public transport, publishing a paragraph or two during a  consultation, but usually at the very end of the consultation period.  Is this due to tardy dissemination of i
[normal]nformation by the County Council, or to editorial policy.? 
[normal]3.4[bold]              [bold]Consultation documents are quite complex, and so only really useable online.  An unusually high proportion of bus passengers probably don’t have access to computers, particularly in rural area
[normal]s lacking in broadband and decent mobile phone signals, leaving paper documents available at libraries. If people rely on public transport, they might only get to the nearest place with a library one day a week for an hour or two to do essential tasks, so 
[normal]would not have time to peruse and respond to a consultation.
[normal]3.5[bold]              [bold]At a public meeting in Felton, I think in October 2011, about cutting bus services to Newton-on-the -Moor and 
[normal]Swarland
[normal], attended by  councillors, council officers, and Arriva representatives 
[normal], it was stated that one of the main ways for determining passenger demand was counting the ticket numbers on services. 
[normal]Local users replied that this could only be done on services which existed, and it did nothing for people needing a bus service which cu[bold]rrently didn’t exist, especially if they had to get a lift to the nearest bus route, often a great distance away[bold] 
[normal]Though  common practice in urban public transport surveys is  to ask people how far and how they travel to and from the service being [bold]surveyed, this is not done in Northumberland.[bold]Most regular passengers using weekly passes suspect that they are waved onto the bus without being counted.
[normal]              
[normal]3.6[bold]              [bold]On regular drivers who know the route and passengers well.  Their employers probably don’t make 
[normal]enough use of their local knowledge, and could run a better service if they did. It is only because of these drivers’ personal dedication that this service operates effectively.
[normal]              
[normal]3.7.i[bold]              [bold]I arrived back in Northumberland in time to see the five year Local Tra
[normal]nsport Plan 2006-2011 apparently voted in by the County Council before the consultation period ended. In autumn 2010, having discovered the name of the Commercial Manager at Arriva, I prepared for the 
[normal]forthcoming 2011 Local Transport Plan by giving out add
[normal]ress cards with the Arriva manager’s name and head office address in Sunderland to anyone who I heard making a comment about the state of the bus service, hoping that it might encourage the decision-makers to pay more attention to our needs and experiences
[normal].  I was much surprised by the number of people who later told me that they had written letters, even those who had said “they won’t listen to us anyway”.  Apparently the Arriva management also got a surprise.  
[normal]ii  [bold]              [bold]Later, questionnaires were distributed 
[normal]to passengers on the 
[normal]Rothbury
[normal] and A1 routes in Northumberland, and collated in the 
[normal]EVIDENCE BASE FOR THE NORTHUMBERLAND LOCAL TRANSPORT  2011-2026, giving the impression of a howl of anguish from passengers.  There was no publicity about this questionnaire[bold] on any of the buses[bold], 
[normal]and it was mostly distributed by passengers who got further copies of it themselves
[normal], and distributed it to everyone they could either on the buses or door-to-door.  Even so, I later heard from many passengers who had still had no idea
[normal] that a consultation was taking place.
[normal]iii  [bold]              [bold]Presusmably[bold]  this was because, as a subsidised service, Arriva ran it under contract for the County Council, and it  did not cover operating consultations or publicity.[bold]              [bold]It is probably not in Arriva’s interests [bold]to facilitate a profitable and effective service if they can get money by contracting to run a service for  the County Council without investing  in market research or promotion.  Few County Council resources available to do this.[bold]On “THE BOTTOM LINE” ON B
[normal]BC RADIO 4 ON 19/11/11, I HEARD DAVID MARTIN, CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF ARRIVA UK appeared to say 
[normal]taht
[normal] 
[normal]there was no money in running public transport services, but Arriva forecast healthy growth by getting  money for running services for councils.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]              [bold]3.8[bold]              [bold]Apparent
