[normal]5) [bold]What are the mai[bold]n challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities?  How can these challenges be overcome?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1[bold]              [bold]Communicating[bold] with passengers and
[normal] potential[bold] passengers (see section 3)
[normal]and, for 
[normal]day-to-day service [bold]changes[bold], recognition from e.g. Arriva, who say that we can use 
[normal]Facebook
[normal] or Twitter, that an unusually high proportion of their passengers don’t have access to or knowledge of these, and many of the most essential journeys are outside of office hours. Arriv
[normal]a’s number for enquiries is only open during office hours, with no numbers for “local” depots. Their 
[normal]Facebook
[normal] page is only updated during office hours.
[normal]There are no information offices on the 
[normal]Thropton
[normal] route outside of Newcastle.
[normal]5.2[bold]              [bold]Accurately establishing
[normal] the need.  
[normal]People have had to give up going to places, make unreliable or inefficient ad hoc arrangements, or get a car when finances or environmental principles make it preferable that they did not.
[normal]If a new service is put in place, especially if it is 
[normal]not publicised, or has not been properly researched to make sure that it best fits peoples’ needs, it takes some time for people to find out about and transfer back to trusting and relying on public transport.  If , as usual it has been a trial period of o
[normal]nly a year, there is not time to build up a base of new and previous customers, and the service is then irrevocably cut due to “lack of demand”.  (Many passengers have concluded that this is probably one of the main objectives when designing “trial periods
[normal]”).
[normal]e.g. the recent history of the Newton-on-the-Moor and 
[normal]Swarland
[normal] bus service, which was no use for workers, and only catered for a small section of the community before it was cut altogether.
[normal]              
[normal]5.3[bold]              [bold]Rough roads and reliability in winter – better 
[normal]integration with highways 
[normal]depts
[normal] – ensuring better gritting times, passing places, and parking /dumping spaces for snow so that cars aren’t parked on roads and buses can get through safely.
